\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total Hamiltonian of all electrons, atoms and the electro-magnetic field
 of a solid state crystal is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H=\sum_{i}\frac{1}{2m_{i}}\left(\mathbf{p}_{i}-ez_{i}\mathbf{A}\left(\mathbf{r}_{i}\right)\right)^{2}+\frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\int\left(\mathbf{E}^{2}+c_{0}^{2}\mathbf{B}^{2}\right)d\mathbf{r}\label{eq:full_crystal_H}\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the second term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\mathbf{E}$"
description "Electrical field"

\end_inset

 denotes the electric- and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\mathbf{B}$"
description "Magnetic field"

\end_inset

the magnetic field.
 These fields are related to the vector potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 and the scalar potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson1998"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\mathbf{E} & =-\frac{\partial\mathbf{A}}{\mathbf{\partial}t}-\nabla\phi\label{eq:E_potentials}\\
\mathbf{B} & =\nabla\times\mathbf{A}.\label{eq:B_vector_potential}\end{align}

\end_inset

In the first term of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:full_crystal_H"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the elementary charge, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the charge of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 (-1 for electrons) and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 denotes the particle mass.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}_{i}-ez_{i}\mathbf{A}\left(\mathbf{r}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the mechanical momentum of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, which is invariant to our gauge choise (see below) for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 The electrical field term 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}^{2}$
\end_inset

 holds both transverse and longitudinal contributions.
 In the following discussion we assume a Coulomb gauge for the vector potential,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\mathbf{A}=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson1998"

\end_inset

.
 In this gauge the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\mathbf{A}}{\partial t}\nabla\phi$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}^{2}$
\end_inset

 vanishes, and so we can split this term to the transverse and longitudinal
 contributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}^{2}=\mathbf{E}_{l}^{2}+\mathbf{E}_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Using Poisson's equation, the longitudinal contribution can be written
 in terms of the charge density 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int\mathbf{E}_{l}^{2}d\mathbf{r}=\int\left(\nabla\phi\right)^{2}d\mathbf{r}=\langle\phi\nabla\phi\rangle-\int\phi\nabla^{2}\phi d\mathbf{r}=\int\phi\frac{\rho}{\epsilon_{0}}d\mathbf{r}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Next, the contributions to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are distinguished between internal 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{int}$
\end_inset

 and external 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{ext}$
\end_inset

, where the internal contributions are created by the crystal electrons
 and atomic cores.
 The internal contributions are given by the longitudinal Coulomb interaction
 between the charged particles 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{i,j}=\frac{e^{2}z_{i}z_{j}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}|\mathbf{r}_{i}-\mathbf{r}_{j}|},\end{equation}

\end_inset

with unit charges 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The external contribution are 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{ext}=\sum_{i}z_{i}e\phi_{ext}(\mathbf{r}_{i}).\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The crystal 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$H$"
description "Hamiltonian operator"

\end_inset

Hamiltonian for electrons 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 and atoms 
\begin_inset Formula $I,J$
\end_inset

 then reads
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
H & = & \underbrace{\sum_{i}\frac{\left(\mathbf{p}_{i}+e\mathbf{A}\right)^{2}}{2m_{0}}}_{T_{e}}+\underbrace{\sum_{I}\frac{\left(\mathbf{p}_{I}+ez_{I}\mathbf{A}\right)^{2}}{2m_{I}}}_{T_{a}}+\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j}\frac{e^{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}|\mathbf{r}_{i}-\mathbf{r}_{j}|}}_{V_{ee}}\nonumber \\
 &  & +\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\sum_{I,J}\frac{e^{2}z_{I}z_{J}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}|\mathbf{r}_{I}-\mathbf{r}_{J}|}}_{V_{aa}}-\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,J}\frac{e^{2}z_{J}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}|\mathbf{r}_{i}-\mathbf{r}_{J}|}}_{V_{ea}}+V_{ext}\nonumber \\
 &  & +\underbrace{\frac{\epsilon_{0}}{2}\int\left(\mathbf{E}_{t}^{2}+c_{0}\mathbf{B}^{2}\right)d\mathbf{r}}_{H_{EM}},\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the kinetic energy part of the Hamiltonian, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 the potential energy one.
 As the atoms have a much higher mass than the electrons, the Born-Oppenheimer
 approximation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yu2005"

\end_inset

 can be used to separate the motion of electrons and atoms.
 The electrons will react on movements of the atoms instantaneously.
 Therefore, the interaction between ion cores and between electrons and
 ion cores can be concentrated into a potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, leading to the final crystal electron Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
H & = & \sum_{i}\left(\frac{\left(\mathbf{p}_{i}+e\mathbf{A}(\mathbf{r}_{i})\right)^{2}}{2m_{0}}+U(\mathbf{r}_{i})\right)\nonumber \\
 &  & +\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i,j}\frac{e^{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}|\mathbf{r}_{i}-\mathbf{r}_{j}|}+V_{ext}+H_{EM}.\label{eq:crystal_H_final}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step is to perform the 
\emph on
single electron approximation
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
mean field approximation
\emph default
 by assuming that the electron-electron interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{ee}$
\end_inset

 with the core- and valence electrons can also be concentrated into the
 potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

.
 This step is necessary as solving the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{23}$
\end_inset

 explicitly considered electrons is an impossible task.
 The equation reduces to a single electron equation, where an electron experienc
es the mean-field potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

.
 Within this step, the vector potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is restricted to external excitations, where the local oscillations within
 the crystal lattice are averaged out.
 Overall, the effect of the external electro-magnetic field on the atoms
 has been excluded.
 This approximation is usually justified in the case of weak fields and
 heavy atomic masses.
 The interaction between electrons and atoms is restricted to a frozen lattice.
 The interaction between the movement of the atoms and the electrons can
 be reintroduced using 
\emph on
phonons
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yu2005"

\end_inset

, but this will be omitted throughout the thesis.
\end_layout

