\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In previous sections, the crystal was assumed to be homogeneous and infinitely
 extended.
 In nanostructures, this assumption is no longer valid and the translational
 symmetry is broken in certain directions.
 As a consequence, a carrier might be energetically confined within a lower-band
gap material, but still free to propagate within the translational invariant
 direction.
 In the case of a quantum well, the symmetry is broken by the atoms of the
 other species in one direction, for a quantum wire, it is broken in two
 directions and for a quantum dot in all three directions.
 Consequently, the number of translational invariant directions is reduced
 from two for a quantum well to zero for a quantum dot.
 As a result, the Bloch function employing the plane wave ansatz has to
 be modified
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\varphi_{m\mathbf{k}_{t}}(\mathbf{r},z)=\sum_{n}u_{n}(\mathbf{r},z)e^{i\mathbf{k}_{t}\cdot\mathbf{r}}F_{n\mathbf{k},m}(z).\label{eq:Envelope_Function_Bloch_Function}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 denotes the coordinate of translational invariant direction(s), 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate of the direction(s) where the crystal symmetry is broken
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}(\mathbf{r},z)$
\end_inset

 is a lattice-periodic function.
 The crystal momentum 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset


\series default
 is only defined within the translational invariant direction.
 The expression 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n\mathbf{k},m}(z)$
\end_inset

 is referred to as slowly-varying envelope and denotes at every position
 in the symmetry broken direction 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, how the lattice-periodic functions are mixed together.
 In the bulk crystal, the plane wave term decouples the wavefunctions with
 different crystal momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

.
 In a nanostructure, this decoupling is only true for the translational
 invariant direction, while in the symmetry broken direction, the states
 are now mixed together.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a result of the symmetry breaking, the bands are split into 
\emph on
subbands
\emph default
, depending on the transverse crystal momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The task of the envelope function method is now to select a suitable set
 of lattice periodic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n}(\mathbf{r},z)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Envelope_Function_Bloch_Function"

\end_inset

 and derive a proper equation to determine the envelopes 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n\mathbf{k},m}(z)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 Envelope Function Ansatz
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The traditional ansatz is to use the zone-center 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 lattice periodic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{n0}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 for the expansion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Envelope_Function_Bloch_Function"

\end_inset

, together with a set of matching conditions.
 The equation for the envelopes is obtained by replacing the wave number
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}$
\end_inset

 by the corresponding operator 
\begin_inset Formula $−i∂_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 As in the nanostructure, different materials are involved, the wavefunction
 is in each material expanded into the materials zone-center functions.
 The result is that the effective mass like parameters from the perturbation
 interaction with remote states and the zone-center energies are position
 dependent.
 For the single-band effective mass approximation for e.g.
 the conduction band in a quantum well for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}_{t}=0$
\end_inset

, the envelope equation is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m^{*}(z)}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial z^{2}}+E_{c}(z)\right)F_{s}(z)=E(0)F_{s}(z).\label{eq:QW_Conduction_Band_Envelope_Schr_Eq}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E_{c}(z)$
\end_inset

 denotes the position dependent bulk band edge, corresponding in the direct
 band gap semiconductors to the conduction band energy at 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Once the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{m}(0)$
\end_inset

 and normalized eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{s,m}(z)$
\end_inset

 (indexed by the subband quantum number 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QW_Conduction_Band_Envelope_Schr_Eq"

\end_inset

 are obtained, the in-plane dispersion is usually approximated using the
 dominant effective mass of the quantum well material
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{m}(\mathbf{k})=E_{m}(0)+\frac{\hbar^{2}k^{2}}{2m_{c}^{*}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The way the equation is written, it is in the presence of a material interface
 not Hermitian and therefore unexpected imaginary eigenvalues for the energy
 would result.
 The usual ad-hoc fix, justified by the requirement of a continuous probability
 flow, is to rewrite the second order differential operator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chuang1995"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m^{*}(z)}\nabla^{2}\rightarrow-\nabla\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m^{*}(z)}\nabla.\label{eq:Second_Order_Diff_Operator}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The particular order of the coefficient and the differential operators is
 commonly referred to as operator ordering.
 The form of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Second_Order_Diff_Operator"

\end_inset

 is denoted as Ben-Daniel and Duke ordering 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BenDaniel1966"

\end_inset

, but within the single-band effective mass theory, other orderings are
 suggested too (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Morrow1984"

\end_inset

 and references therein).
 The ordering is irrelevant within bulk materials, but plays a substantial
 role at a material interface: it is equivalent to the matching conditions
 for the bulk Bloch functions.
 In the case of a multi-band equation, where not only one, but several lattice
 periodic functions are included, one obtains in analogy to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Second_Order_Diff_Operator"

\end_inset

 for all envelopes involved 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}(z)=(F_{1}(z),F_{2}(z),...,F_{M}(z))^{T}$
\end_inset

 a system of coupled partial differential equations
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{H}_{\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}}(z)\mathbf{F}(z)=E\mathbf{F}(z),\label{eq:General_Envelope_Function_Schr_Eq}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 differential operator is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\mathbf{H}_{\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}}(z) & = & -\sum_{i,j}\partial_{i}\mathbf{H}_{i,j}^{(2)}(\mathbf{r};\mathbf{k}_{t})\partial_{j}\nonumber \\
 &  & +\sum_{i}\left(\mathbf{H}_{i;L}^{(1)}(\mathbf{r};\mathbf{k}_{t})\partial_{i}+\partial_{i}\mathbf{H}_{i;R}^{(1)}(\mathbf{r};\mathbf{k}_{t})\right)\nonumber \\
 &  & +\mathbf{H}^{(0)}(\mathbf{r};\mathbf{k}_{t}).\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Here the Hermitian operator ordering has already been introduced.
 The problem is that within the bulk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 Hamiltonian, terms of the type 
\begin_inset Formula $Nk_{i}k_{j}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 can appear, for which the operator ordering is not clear.
 The usual fix is to split the contribution symmetrically
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
Nk_{i}k_{j}\rightarrow\partial_{i}\frac{N}{2}\partial_{j}-\partial_{j}\frac{N}{2}\partial_{i}.\label{eq:Symmetrized_Operator_Ordering}\end{equation}

\end_inset

It can be shown that this particular choice, which is called 
\emph on
symmetrized operator ordering
\emph default
, may lead to erroneous results.
 The traditional envelope equations for one and several bands are widely
 applied and used in a variety of numerical calculations of quantum wells
 (and superlattices) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Altarelli1983,Bastard1981,Bastard1982,Eppenga1987,Chuang1991"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beside its successful application to some material systems, the traditional
 way of deriving the envelope equations contains several ad hoc fixes, which
 are required within the presence of material interfaces.
 The operator ordering is crucial at a material interface, where the material
 parameters change and therefore the ad-hoc operator ordering involves unknown
 approximations made to the effect of the interface.
 
