\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{15}$
\end_inset

 states, while the valence band states have contributions from all except
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 states.
 The corresponding terms are given by the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{r}^{4\times4}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Remote_Contributions_Hamiltonian"

\end_inset

 and the coefficients 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Hr4_Coefficients"

\end_inset

.
 In deriving these terms, the energy for the energy-dependent renormalization
 has been replaced by the according band edge energies 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Although the approximation might be reasonable for very remote bands 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, it remains crude.
 The derivation of the terms tese terms involves only symmetry arguments
 similar to the already used arguments within this chapter.
 The bar in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{A_{c}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{M}$
\end_inset

 indicates the close relationship to the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{A_{c},}\tilde{L}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{M}$
\end_inset

 , which include the free-electron dispersion
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{A_{c}}=\bar{A_{c}}+\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m_{0}},\,\,\tilde{L}'=\bar{L}+\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m_{0}},\,\,\tilde{M}=\bar{M}+\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m_{0}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

whereas in this case the free electron dispersion is still contained in
 the direct interaction matrix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Direct_Int_Matrix"

\end_inset

.
 The operator ordering in the offdiagonal terms 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{y}\tilde{N}_{+}k_{x}+k_{x}\tilde{N}_{-}k_{y}$
\end_inset

 has been derived by Foreman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Foreman1995b"

\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{+}$
\end_inset

 contains the contribution from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{1}\,(F)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{12}\,(G)$
\end_inset

 bands, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{-}$
\end_inset

 contains the contributions from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{15}\,(H_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{25}\,(H_{2})$
\end_inset

 bands.
 In the bulk 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 theory, the ordering is irrelevant and the terms are summed together into
 the Kane's parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}'$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{N}'=\tilde{N}_{+}+\tilde{N}_{-}.\label{eq:Kane_Parameter}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Within the traditional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}·\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 envelope function method applied to heterostructure, the symmetrized operator
 ordering 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Symmetrized_Operator_Ordering"

\end_inset

 simply uses
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{N}_{+}=\tilde{N}_{-}=\frac{\tilde{N'}}{2}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{L}'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}$
\end_inset

 are usually determined by calculating analytical expressions for the dispersion
 and relating them to measured effective masses.
 The detailed splitting of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}'$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{-}$
\end_inset

 is not directly accessible from experiment, but can be estimated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Foreman1993"

\end_inset

 using the following arguments: The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{-}$
\end_inset

 contains contributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{15}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{25}$
\end_inset

 bands.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{25}$
\end_inset

 bands can only be formed by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

-type and higher atomic orbitals, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{15}$
\end_inset

 bands can be formed by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-,
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-,
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

- and higher type orbitals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Foreman1995b"

\end_inset

.
 Within the usual semiconductors, the influence of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 orbitals is insignificant.
 Therefore, neglecting the influence of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{25}$
\end_inset

 bands (
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}=0$
\end_inset

) and using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Hr4_Coefficients"

\end_inset

, the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{-}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{N}_{-}=\bar{M}=\tilde{M}-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m_{o}}.\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{+}$
\end_inset

 can be deduced using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Kane_Parameter"

\end_inset

 and the experimentally determined value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}'$
\end_inset

.
 In a usual zinc-blende semiconductor such as 
\begin_inset Formula $GaAs$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{M}$
\end_inset

 = −2.65 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}'$
\end_inset

 = −17.4 (in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m_{0}}$
\end_inset

).
 The symmetric operator ordering would therefore use 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{+/-}$
\end_inset

 = −8.7, while the Burt-Foreman ordering gives strongly asymmetric values
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{+}$
\end_inset

= −13.75 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{-}$
\end_inset

 = −3.65.
 In contrast to the operator ordering within the valence band, the ordering
 in the off-diagonal terms between the conduction and valence bands, given
 by the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{y}Ck_{z}+k_{z}Ck_{y}$
\end_inset

, is required to be symmetric.
 Only remote 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{15}$
\end_inset

 type bands mix into the 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-type conduction band, and therefore, the non-vanishing elements from the
 perturbation are
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k_{y}\left\langle s\mid p_{y}\mid y^{r}\right\rangle \left\langle y^{r}\mid p_{z}\mid x\right\rangle k_{z}+k_{z}\left\langle s\mid p_{z}\mid y^{r}\right\rangle \left\langle z^{r}\mid p_{y}\mid x\right\rangle k_{y}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

By crystal symmetry, these terms are equal.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is related to the common Kane parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $B=2C$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is usually small, it is commonly neglected, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C=0$
\end_inset

.
