\begin_layout Standard
The here elaborated model, including the CB, HH, LH and SO band, is commonly
 referred to as the 
\begin_inset Formula $8\times8$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 model.
 For large band gap materials, the coupling between the conduction and valence
 bands is weak and therefore the 
\begin_inset Formula $8\times8$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 model can be divided into to a 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times6$
\end_inset

 model, including only the valence bands and a single band model for the
 spin degenerate conduction band.
 This division is achieved by perturbatively folding the conduction band
 onto the valence bands and vice versa.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times6$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 is therefore obtained by using only the valence band part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{rd}^{8\times8}+\mathbf{H}_{SO,\mathbf{p}}$
\end_inset

 with modified parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $L′$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N′$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L'=\tilde{L}'+\frac{P^{2}}{E_{g}},\,\,\,\, N_{+}=\tilde{N}_{+}+\frac{P^{2}}{E_{g}}\label{eq:Kanes_params_renormalization}\end{equation}

\end_inset

instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{L}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{+}$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{M}$
\end_inset

, and consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{N}_{-}$
\end_inset

, remain unchanged.
 Thereby, the correct operator ordering is conserved.
 The conduction band parameter is obtained using
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A_{c}=\tilde{A}_{c}+\frac{P^{2}}{E_{g}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is then equal to the common conduction band effective mass.
 For some semiconductors, the spin-orbit splitting is large and the SO band
 has only little influence on the top of the valence band.
 Then, the 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times6$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 model can be further reduced to only include the HH and LH bands.
 The reduction is performed by choosing a combination of basis functions
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:levels_basis_with_spin"

\end_inset

 effectively diagonalizing the spin-orbit interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{SO,\mathbf{p}}$
\end_inset

.
 The new basis is labelled according to its total angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 and the angular momentum around the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-axis, 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 A possible choice, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|J,J_{z}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as notation, is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
u_{hh}=\left|\frac{3}{2},\frac{3}{2}\right\rangle  & = & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|x\uparrow\right\rangle +i\left|y\uparrow\right\rangle \right),\nonumber \\
u_{lh}=\left|\frac{3}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right\rangle  & = & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\left(\left|x\downarrow\right\rangle +i\left|y\uparrow\right\rangle \right)+\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}\left|z\uparrow\right\rangle ,\nonumber \\
\bar{u}_{lh}=\left|\frac{3}{2},-\frac{1}{2}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\left(\left|x\uparrow\right\rangle -i\left|y\uparrow\right\rangle \right)+\sqrt{\frac{2}{3}}\left|z\downarrow\right\rangle ,\label{eq:Angular_Momentum_Basis}\\
\bar{u}_{hh}=\left|\frac{3}{2},-\frac{3}{2}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|x\downarrow\right\rangle -i\left|y\downarrow\right\rangle \right),\nonumber \\
u_{SO}=\left|\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\left(\left|x\downarrow\right\rangle +i\left|y\downarrow\right\rangle +\left|z\uparrow\right\rangle \right),\nonumber \\
\bar{u}_{SO}=\left|\frac{1}{2},-\frac{1}{2}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\left(\left|x\uparrow\right\rangle -i\left|y\uparrow\right\rangle -\left|z\downarrow\right\rangle \right).\nonumber \end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The four states with total angular momentum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{3}{2}$
\end_inset

 belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{8}$
\end_inset

 and the two states with an angular momentum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 form the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{7}$
\end_inset

 (or SO) bands.
 Transforming the Hamiltonian into the basis 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Angular_Momentum_Basis"

\end_inset

 and neglecting the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{7}$
\end_inset

 rows and columns finally results in the 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 model.
 Within the 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 model, it is common to use the Luttinger parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{1},\gamma_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{3}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The full listing of these parameters is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chuang1995"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Luttinger1956"

\end_inset

 instead of the Kane's parameters of the 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times6$
\end_inset

 model 
\begin_inset Formula $L′,\, M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N′$
\end_inset

.
 The Luttinger parameters are usually those given in literature.
 The parameters are related to each other via
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
L' & = & -\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m_{0}}\left(\gamma_{1}+4\gamma_{2}\right)\nonumber \\
M & = & -\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m_{0}}\left(\gamma_{1}-2\gamma_{2}\right)\label{eq:Luttinger_Kane_parameters_relation}\\
