\begin_layout Standard
The conduction band can be modeled quite easily if we assume that the interactio
n with the other bands is weak enough for it to be treated perturbatively,
 i.e.
 use a simple effective mass model.
 In the case of the valence band, however, the strong interaction between
 the degenerate light and heavy hole bands (near the band edge) requires
 that these bands are taken into account explicitly.
 Only when we consider energy levels deep into the valence bands (close
 to the SO splitting energy, about 
\begin_inset Formula $300\, meV$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $GaAs)$
\end_inset

 do the coupling terms to the SO and conduction bands (
\begin_inset Formula $1.5\, eV$
\end_inset

 splitting) can be introduced through the effective mass.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The degeneracy of the light and heavy hole bands near the band edge generates
 a coupling term (as in the Luttinger Hamiltonian).
 Including spin degeneracy, this yields a set of four coupled effective
 mass equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Andreani1987,Chuang1995,broido_effective_1985"

\end_inset

.
 Fortunately, this set of coupled equations can be greatly simplified by
 a method described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "broido_effective_1985"

\end_inset

.
 Here a unitary transformation of the four basis Bloch functions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Angular_Momentum_Basis"

\end_inset

 into a new set 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{A},u_{B},u_{C,}u_{D}$
\end_inset

 to decouple the set of four coupled equations into two coupled ones.
 The Bloch functions 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 are given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
u_{A} & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(u_{hh}-\bar{u}_{hh}\right),\\
u_{B} & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(-u_{lh}-\bar{u}_{lh}\right),\\
u_{C} & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(u_{lh}+\bar{u}_{lh}\right),\\
u_{D} & = & \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(u_{hh}+\bar{u}_{hh}\right).\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Consequently, the 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{H}^{4\times4}=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
P-Q & -S^{\dagger} & 0 & R\\
-S & P+Q & R & 0\\
0 & R^{\dagger} & P-Q & S\\
R^{\dagger} & 0 & S^{\dagger} & P+Q\end{array}\right).\end{equation}

\end_inset

In terms of the the new base proposed above, it can be diagonalized into
 two 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 block matrices, upper 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{U}$
\end_inset

 and lower 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{L}$
\end_inset

, given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H^{\sigma}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
P\pm Q & W\\
W^{\dagger} & P\mp Q\end{array}\right),\label{eq:Block_2_2_H}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\left|R\right|-i\left|S\right|$
\end_inset

.
 The index 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=U(L)$
\end_inset

 refers to the upper (lower) 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 signs.
 The upper and lower blocks are equivalent, showing the double degeneracy
 of the heavy and light hole bands.
 It is therefore sufficient to solve the upper block and obtain its solutions.
 The solutions of the lower block can easily be determined from the latter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can identify 
\begin_inset Formula $P-Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P+Q$
\end_inset

 with the light hole energy (operator) 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{lh}$
\end_inset

 and the heavy hole energy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{hh}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Similarly to the conduction band case, the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Schr
\backslash
"{o}dinger 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equation with the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Block_2_2_H"

\end_inset

 can be simplified into an effective-mass formalism with 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\hat{H}_{lh} & = & -\left(\gamma_{1}+2\gamma_{2}\right)\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial z^{2}}+\left(\gamma_{1}-\gamma_{2}\right)k_{t}^{2},\\
\hat{H}_{hh} & = & -\left(\gamma_{1}-2\gamma_{2}\right)\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial z^{2}}+\left(\gamma_{1}+\gamma_{2}\right)k_{t}^{2},\\
\hat{W} & = & \left\{ \begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{c}
\sqrt{3}k_{t}\left(\gamma_{2}k_{t}-2\gamma_{3}\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\right)\,\,\,\textrm{for}\,[100]\end{array}\\
\begin{array}{c}
\sqrt{3}k_{t}\left(\gamma_{3}k_{t}-2\gamma_{3}\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\right)\,\,\,\textrm{for}\,[110]\end{array}\end{array}\right.\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Finally, we take into account the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(z)$
\end_inset

, which represents the (bulk) valence-band-edge offset with respect to an
 arbitrary reference energy.
 This allows us write the effective mass equation as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\hat{H}_{hh}+V & \hat{W}\\
\hat{W}^{\dagger} & \hat{H}_{lh}+V\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
F_{hh}\\
F_{lh}\end{array}\right)=E(\mathbf{k})\left(\begin{array}{c}
F_{hh}\\
F_{lh}\end{array}\right),\label{eq:Effective_Mass_Equation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{hh}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{lh}$
\end_inset

 are the envelope functions corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{B}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Note that in this formalism, hole energies are taken to be positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step in solving the quantum well problem, is finding the solution
 in bulk material, where we take 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to be a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 will be different in well material and barriers reflecting the different
 valence band edge offsets.
 We can now easily solve for the eigenenergies 
\begin_inset Formula $E(\mathbf{k})$
\end_inset

, yielding the bulk energy dispersion relations for the heavy and light
 hole subbands.
 We consider the case of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[100\right]$
\end_inset

 plane, writing the in-plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 component as 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E(\mathbf{k})-V_{0}=\gamma_{1}\left(k_{z}^{2}+k_{t}^{2}\right)\pm\sqrt{4\gamma_{2}^{2}\left(k_{z}^{2}+k_{t}^{2}\right)+12\left(\gamma_{3}^{2}-\gamma_{2}^{2}\right)k_{z}^{2}k_{t}^{2}},\label{eq:Bulk_Dispersion_Relation_HH_LH}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the plus sign refers to the light hole solution, and the minus to
 the heavy hole one.
 This expression can be rewritten to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E(\mathbf{k})=V_{0}+\left[\gamma_{1}\pm\gamma_{2}\sqrt{1+3\frac{\gamma_{3}^{2}-\gamma_{2}^{2}}{\gamma_{2}^{2}}\frac{k_{z}^{2}k_{t}^{2}}{\left(k_{z}^{2}+k_{t}^{2}\right)^{2}}}\right]\left(k_{z}^{2}+k_{t}^{2}\right).\end{equation}

\end_inset

A similar derivation can be formulated for the [110] crystal planes.
\end_layout

