\begin_layout Standard
In the discussion so far have concentrated solely on solving systems for
 a single charge carrier.
 In many devices such models would be inadequate as large numbers of charge
 carriers, e.g.
 electrons, can be present in the conduction band.
 In order to decide whether or not typical carrier densities would give
 rise to a significant additional potential on top of the usual band-edge
 potential terms (which will be labelled specifically as 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{CB}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{VB}$
\end_inset

), it then becomes necessary to solve the electrostatics describing the
 system.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model Formulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When considering the case of an n-type material, then (although obvious)
 it is worth stating that the number of free electrons in the conduction
 band is equal to the number of positively charged ionized donors in the
 heterostructure.
 As an example, we can point out the modulation doped system, where the
 doping is located in a position where the free carriers it produces will
 become spatially separated from the ion.
 The additional potential term 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\rho}(z)$
\end_inset

 arising from this, or any other charge distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, can be expressed by using Poisson's equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\nabla^{2}V_{\rho}=-\frac{\rho}{\epsilon}\label{eq:Poissons_Eq}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the permittivity of the material, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=\epsilon_{r}\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The solution is generally obtained via the electric field strength 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Recalling that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}=-\nabla V\end{equation}

\end_inset

the potential then follow in the usual way 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jackson1998"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{\rho}(z)=-\int_{-\infty}^{\mathbf{r}}\mathbf{E}\cdot d\mathbf{r}.\label{eq:Poisson_Potential}\end{equation}

\end_inset

Given that the potential profiles, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{CB}(Z)$
\end_inset

 for example, are one-dimensional, then they will also produce a one-dimensional
 charge distribution.
 In addition, remembering that the quantum wells are assumed infinite in
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $x-y$
\end_inset

 plane then any charge density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(z)$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as an infinite plane, i.e.
 a sheet, with areal charge density 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(z)$
\end_inset

 and thickness 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta z$
\end_inset

, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Electric_Field_Enfinite_Plane"

\end_inset

(a).
 
