Such an infinite plane of charge produces an electric field perpendicular
 to it, and with a strength
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}=\frac{\sigma}{2\epsilon}.\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that as the sheet is infinite in the plane, then the field strength
 is constant for all distances from the plane.
 The total electric field strength due to many of these planes of charge,
 as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Electric_Field_Enfinite_Plane"

\end_inset

(b), is then the sum of the individual contributions as follows
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}(z)=\sum_{z'=-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{\sigma(z')}{2\epsilon}\textrm{sign}\left(z-z'\right)\label{eq:Electrical_Field_Poisson}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the function sign is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\textrm{sign}\left(z\right)=\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
1,\,\,\,\, z\geq0\\
-1,\,\,\,\, z\leq0\end{array}\right.\end{equation}

\end_inset

and has been introduced to account for the vector nature of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 if a single sheet of charge is at a position 
\begin_inset Formula $z'$
\end_inset

, then for 
\begin_inset Formula $z>z'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}(z)=+\nicefrac{\sigma}{2\epsilon}$
\end_inset

, whereas for 
\begin_inset Formula $z<z'$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}(z)=-\nicefrac{\sigma}{2\epsilon}$
\end_inset

.
 Note further that it is only the charge neutrality, there are as many ionized
 donors (or acceptors) in the system as there are electrons (or holes),
 or expressed mathematically
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{z=-\infty}^{\infty}\sigma(z)=0,\end{equation}

\end_inset

which ensures that the electric field, and hence the potential, go to zero
 at large distances from the charge distribution.
 For the case of a doped semiconductor, there would be two contributions
 to the charge density 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(z)$
\end_inset

, where the first would be the ionized impurities and the second the free
 charge carriers themselves.
 While the former would be known from the doping density in each semiconductor
 layer, as defined at growth time, the latter would be calculated from the
 probability distributions of the carriers in the heterostructure.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $d(z)$
\end_inset

 defines the volume density of the dopants at position 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, where the planes are separated by the usual step length 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta z$
\end_inset

, then the total number of carriers, per unit cross-sectional area, introduced
 into the heterostructure is given by
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
N=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}d(z)dz.\end{equation}

\end_inset

The net charge density in any of the planes follows as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma(z)=q\left[N\psi^{*}(z)\psi(z)-d(z)\right]\delta z\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 us the charge on the extrinsic carriers.
 The step length 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta z$
\end_inset

 selects the proportion of the carriers that are within that slab and converts
 the volume density of dopant, 
\begin_inset Formula $d(z)$
\end_inset

, into an areal density.
 
