\begin_layout Standard
We formulate the statistical distribution of 2DEG electrons.
 The free electrons occupy the energy levels in the quantum well according
 to the Fermi-Dirac distribution 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f(E)=\frac{1}{1+e^{\frac{E-E_{F}}{k_{B}T}}},\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{F}$
\end_inset

 is the chemical potential of the electrons, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the Boltzman constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 the temperature.
 In order to calculate the Fermi energy, the 2D density of states should
 be multiplied by this statistical distribution and integrated over all
 possible states.
 We concentrate on the low temperature regime (
\begin_inset Formula $T\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

), and assuming that all available states are occupied in the first conduction
 subband, the Fermi energy of the system equals the electron chemical potential
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
E_{F}=E_{E_{1}}(0)+\frac{\pi\hbar^{2}}{m_{e}^{*}}n_{e},\label{eq:Fermi_Energy_2DEG}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{E_{1}}(0)$
\end_inset

 denotes the bottom of the first conduction subband, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the Boltzman constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 the temperature.
 The wavevector of the top most occupied state thus becomes (assuming a
 parabolic dispersion) 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k_{F}=\sqrt{\frac{2m_{e}^{*}}{\hbar^{2}}E_{F}}=\sqrt{2\pi n_{e}}.\label{eq:Fermi_Wavevector_2DEG}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

